 16)", "borderLeftColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderTopWidth": "0px", "borderRightWidth": "0px", "borderBottomWidth": "0px", "borderLeftWidth": "0px", "borderTopLeftRadius": "0px", "borderTopRightRadius": "0px", "borderBottomLeftRadius": "0px", "borderBottomRightRadius": "0px", "paddingTop": "8px", "paddingRight": "0px", "paddingBottom": "8px", "paddingLeft": "0px", "marginTop": "0px", "marginRight": "0px", "marginBottom": "8px", "marginLeft": "0px", "textAlign": "left", "boxShadow": "none", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "imageCount": 0, "interactiveCount": 0}]}], "bodyStyles": {"fontSize": "17px", "fontWeight": "400", "fontFamily": "system-ui, -apple-system, \"system-ui\", \"Segoe UI\", Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif", "color": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "backgroundColor": "rgb(253, 248, 242)", "display": "block", "position": "static", "borderTopColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderRightColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderBottomColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderLeftColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderTopWidth": "0px", "borderRightWidth": "0px", "borderBottomWidth": "0px", "borderLeftWidth": "0px", "borderTopLeftRadius": "0px", "borderTopRightRadius": "0px", "borderBottomLeftRadius": "0px", "borderBottomRightRadius": "0px", "paddingTop": "0px", "paddingRight": "0px", "paddingBottom": "0px", "paddingLeft": "0px", "marginTop": "0px", "marginRight": "0px", "marginBottom": "0px", "marginLeft": "0px", "textAlign": "start", "boxShadow": "none", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "htmlRect": {"x": 0, "y": 0, "width": 1440, "height": 2530.19, "bottom": 2530.19, "right": 1440, "area": 3643470}, "visibleText": "Copper Kettle Suppers Featured Recipe Ingredients Method Tips & Swaps About the Cook The Pantry List The Pantry List What You'll Need Gather everything before the pot meets the flame. The recipe leans on a short list\n      of well-chosen building blocks \u2014 good shanks, dry herbs, an honest splash of vermouth \u2014\n      so quality matters more than quantity. Quantities below serve four generously. Lamb & Marinade 7 items 4 meaty lamb shanks, ~380 g each, trimmed of excess fat 2 tbsp coarse sea salt, for the dry cure 1 tbsp cracked black peppercorns 6 sprigs fresh rosemary, lightly bruised 4 cloves garlic, smashed with the flat of a knife 2 strips lemon zest, pith removed 3 tbsp olive oil, for searing White Bean Ragout 9 items 350 g dried cannellini beans, soaked overnight (or 2 \u00d7 400 g tins, drained) 1 large yellow onion, finely diced 2 medium carrots, cut into 1 cm dice 2 ribs celery, cut into 1 cm dice 6 oil-packed anchovy fillets, finely chopped 2 tbsp tomato paste, double-concentrated 120 ml dry white vermouth (Noilly Prat preferred) 700 ml rich lamb or chicken stock, warmed 1 bay leaf and 2 sprigs thyme, tied with kitchen string Finishing Touches 4 items 1 small handful flat-leaf parsley, roughly chopped 1 tsp finely grated lemon zest, for brightness 2 tbsp good extra-virgin olive oil, for drizzling \u2014 flaky sea salt and coarse black pepper, to taste Acceptable Substitutions No vermouth? A dry white wine such as Vermentino or Pinot Grigio will do, though\n        the finished ragout will lose a touch of its herbaceous edge. Anchovies can be\n        swapped for 1 tbsp white miso for a similar umami backbone. Tinned cannellini\n        skip the overnight soak \u2014 add them in the final 30 minutes only, or they will\n        collapse into the sauce. Continue to Method \u00a9 Copper Kettle Suppers \u00b7 A single-recipe showcase \u00b7 hello@copperkettlesuppers.test"}